Department of Chemistry, Radiochemistry Laboratory

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Canadian Journal of Chemistry, Vol.45, p.1149 (1967)

x4freetext: The Energy Degradation was Calculated According to
R.M. Sternheimer, Phys.Rev.115,137(1959)
Used For Proton Energies Up to 15 MeV
Used For Proton Energies Greater Than 15 MeV
Cu-63(P,N)
Renormalized Values
For Cu-65(P,X)
Mixtures of Spectroscopically Pure Cu-Oxide and Sr-
Nitrate, Enriched to 98.82 and 99.84% Sr-88,
Respectively. Impurities were Insignificant and did
Not Influence the Results. The Mixture was Loaded Into
An Aluminium Tube, Which was Rolled Flat to Make a Thin
And Uniform Target. The Energy Degradation of the Beam
By Such a Target was Found to be Within the Reported
Energy Spread of the Beam (+-2 MEV).
Corrections were Made For Chemical Yield, Aliquot
Factor, Branching Ratio, Internal Conversion
Coefficients, and For Decay During and After the
Irradiation.
Lapf
Some Corrections have Been Included by
CAJAD
Lower Case.
V.Mc-Lane`S Remark is Included
Last checking has been done.
The Error of the Cross Sections is Estimated
To be 12%.
This Value was Obtained by Taking the Square Root
Of the Sum of the Squares of the Uncertainties Which
Include Errors in the Estimation of Photopeak Areas,
Decay Curve Analysis, Efficiencies of the Detection
Equipment, Chemical Yields, Pipetting, Weighing, and
Energy Spread in the Beam. Not Included are Errors
Connected with the Decay Schemes As Half-Lives, Con-
Version Coefficients, Branching Ratios and Errors of
The Monitor Cross Sections.

x4freetext: In the Paper of Gadioli Et Al. Calculated Excitation
Functions are Compared to Experimental Data of Several
Authors. The Results of Sachdev Et Al. Below 30 MeV
Were Assumed to be Overestimated. This was Concluded
By Comparing Total Reaction Cross Sections Measured
Via the Beam Attenuation Method to a Cross Section
Calculated As the Sum of the Individual Cross Sections
As Quoted by Sachdev. This Sum Reveals a Much Larger
Value Than the Directly Measured Total Reaction Cross
Section.

x4freetext: High Spin State  (4-). In the Meanwhile There was Found
A Low Spin State (1+) With a Half-Life of 4.6 Sec Which
Decays Via B+ and Ec Transitions to Sr-84. Since No
Isomeric Transition was Found, It is Unclear Which
Isomer is the Ground State. It is Adopted by the
Compiler That the Measured Cross Section is Only
Partial. This Assumption is Supported by Comparisons
With Calculations, Where the Experimental Values
Are Low (SEE E.GADIOLI ET AL., PHYS.REV.C16,1404,1977)
(COMMENT BY THE COMPILER OF KACHAPAG).
